  "texts": [
    "Our proposed disclosure extension (iii) is to advocate for the creation of 6 For instance, the closest the British Polling Council gets to disclosure standards on the procedures to generate survey weights can be found in their membership agreement: \"[...] the public opinion polling organisation responsible for conducting the survey that has entered the public domain will place the following information on its own web site within 2 working days of the data being published.[...",
    "]A description of any weighting, filtering, modelling or imputation procedures that have been employed, the weighted/modelled and (where relevant) unweighted figures for all variables (demographic or otherwise) used to weight the data (irrespective of whether or not such variables appear in any tabulated analyses of the data), and the source(s) of the data used to set weighting targets[...]\" (British Polling Council 2023).",
    "a benchmark stratification frame, to be published by any of the polling associations mentioned above, which includes a minimal set of cells.",
    "For example, this benchmark frame could break down the British population by constituency, sex, age and education, where each dimension is assigned very simple categories compatible with a large variety of pollster-specific design choices (e.g., sex:{male, female}, age: {18-64,65+}, education: {has uni.",
    "education, does not have uni. education}; etc."
  ]
}